The Higgs boson analyzed
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson caused quite a stir last summer, and with good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
Finally, it is the last particle whose existence was predicted by the Standard Model - our best, or &quot;least wrong&quot; explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but not yet observed empirically.
But for the physicists it is not yet completely certain that it really is the Higgs.
We know beyond a shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle and that it closely resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
Moreover, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented at a major physics congress in Kyoto this week, but data are still lacking to be completely sure.
Still, let&#39;s assume it&#39;s actually the Higgs, since there seems to be little risk of being wrong, and let&#39;s see what it&#39;s all about.
There is an inescapably unavoidable law in this world which means that two objects cannot exist in the same place at the same time.
It is not possible to break this rule - and don&#39;t try too hard, as you will hurt yourself.
Because even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that such a law also applies to it: Pauli&#39;s exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the are in the same &quot;quantum state&quot;, which &quot;state&quot; consists broadly of some of their properties.
Based on this, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In a corner are the good citizens, known as fermione, who politely obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other move the bosons, an evil gang of anarchists who hold nothing sacred - certainly not this principle, which means they may indeed be in the same place at the same time.
According to the Berkeley Laboratories&#39; website The Particle Adventure (which is absolutely amazing, by the way), these bosons fall into two groups: the mesons, which we won&#39;t discuss here, and the &quot;force particles,&quot; through which the great forces of nature propagate and to which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
However, it must be emphasized here that these bosons are not all such exotic creatures as one might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, it is only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or &quot;light particle&quot; which is the &quot;messenger&quot; of the electromagnetic force.
When a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, the electromagnetic field is &quot;perturbed&quot; at that precise location, somewhat like a pebble thrown into a pond.
This &quot;disturbance&quot; creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon and thus one of the bosons &quot;carriers of force&quot;.
More stable field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, has to be &quot;perturbed&quot; for this boson to show up.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the exciter has to reach very high energies, somewhat comparable to a frozen pond whose surface could only be furrowed by a very large rock.
That&#39;s why a giant particle accelerator like CERN is needed - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring 27 km in circumference! - to achieve such energies.
The electromagnetic field analogy is again helpful in explaining the relationship between the Higgs and mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others don&#39;t - for example, a sheet of paper would never stick to the fridge by itself.
And likewise, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have mass, while the others (like the photon, incidentally) have no mass.
Now what can all this research &quot;be good for,&quot; asks Ms. Plamondon?
For science, they serve to test the Standard Model (SM), and they also allow physicists to examine in detail any discrepancies between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
Incidentally, there are many physicists who eagerly hope that such discrepancies will be found, since the slightest difference could open a door to a &quot;new physics&quot; and plug some holes in the model.
It has to be said that the latter still has major shortcomings, since it doesn&#39;t offer an explanation of gravity (oops!) and dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter in the universe (oops again!).
However, such deviations have not yet been found at CERN.
Effects
The impact of this research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume there isn&#39;t.
By the way: in the early 1960s, the laser pioneers in the Bell Laboratories did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who developed the first continuous wave laser himself (the first ones were pulsed) in 1962 - has already told us that the laser was initially seen more as a &quot;laboratory gimmick&quot;.
Imagine...
In addition, applications can also arise from all the tools surrounding research.
For example, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969 while working in optics.
Although it wasn&#39;t its original purpose, this sensor now serves as the &quot;eye&quot; for all digital cameras worldwide and earned it the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily change our lives, but it does mean that you really never know...
