In addition, as so often in these technologies, a political vision is tangible: the conviction that the current monetary system, designed by bank monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), Bitcoin is both a virtual currency (but convertible into dollars, euros, etc.) and a protocol for secure exchanges like BitTorrent, which allows files to be exchanged directly.
With 15,000 computers in the network, around 200,000 transactions have already been recorded.
A few thousand websites accept bitcoin as a donation or as a form of payment.
After peaking at $30 in June 2011, Bitcoin&#39;s price fell to $2 five months later before recovering to around $10 today (prices are listed on bitcoincharts.com). ).
Nothing particularly impressive compared to world trading of real currencies or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
She describes Bitcoin as &quot;the most successful virtual currency&quot;, &quot;competing with the dollar or euro&quot; and &quot;similar to traditional currencies&quot;.
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currency such as the &quot;credits&quot; used to advance in a video game, which can be won or bought (and sometimes exchanged back) by playing.
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, the trade is always controlled and processed by a central authority.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously custodians of the account book, auditors, issuers of money, as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Any transaction between two users actually takes place between two email addresses in the form of an email.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A number of data related to this transaction are electronically signed by a double encryption system.
This allows the network to verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Using the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the bitcoins traded are present in the ledger of public accounts distributed throughout the network.
The crucial step is to enter this new transaction in this book.
This is done via a math problem launched on the computers, with the winner, who is a sort of interim central banker, having the privilege of adding that extra line.
It is file fragmentation, ie converting a large file into a shorter and unique electronic fingerprint.
The computers &quot;take&quot; the new transaction and add a number to it before &quot;hacking&quot; the whole thing.
The goal is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
When this number is found, the other nodes can easily check if it&#39;s the right one.
The transaction is thus permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a user wants to cheat twice using the same money very quickly (less than 10 minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other would remain unlinked since both have different fingerprints.
The computer that has solved the task receives 50 bitcoins.
To prevent inflation, this reward will be halved regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The Bitcoins in circulation are thus limited to 21 million, but divisible to a hundred millionth, which leaves a certain leeway...
In addition, the difficulty of the task increases with each improvement in computing power.
The life of the network has already had ups and downs.
The websites that provide services for bitcoin were attacked and the bitcoin deposits were stolen.
&quot;The exploited vulnerability does not affect the actual protocol,&quot; assures Pierre Noizat, who just launched Paymium, which is a real-money payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on money laundering opportunities using this anonymous service.
However, cash also has these shortcomings.
Important actors like Wikipedia refuse donations of this kind.
They are accepted by others such as the WordPress blog platform.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the ledger and showed that almost 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
A &quot;mega sale&quot; was launched in November.
&quot;Thirty thousand dollars were exchanged,&quot; said Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, a company that converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a book on this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
Its Paytunia system is equivalent to a credit card (with real money) or a contactless payment with a mobile phone, but uses bitcoin to validate transactions, making them cheaper.
In addition, the owner manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented by traders and the latter do not need to install new terminals or computer programs.
All you have to do is enter an address that can be &quot;photographed and recognized&quot; by a phone, says Pierre Noizat, who assures that he has thousands of users.
There is a general trend of rethinking hierarchical systems in favor of more horizontal systems.
&quot;It will take some time for bitcoin to catch on, but 2013 could be a turning point,&quot; he predicts.
Incidentally, the ECB&#39;s report provides for a reassessment of the various risks that are currently considered to be high should this currency succeed.
We pulled out of Afghanistan.
And then?
French troops have left their area of responsibility in Afghanistan (Kapisa and Surobi).
NATO and the US are expected to follow at the end of 2014.
It is time for the Afghan army to retake possession of its territory and for the Afghan people to decide their future without expecting anything from us.
In particular, we have punished the Afghan peasants by considering them terrorists.
And ourselves with our 88 killed soldiers, as well as the injured and disabled.
The Taliban are made up of foreign extremists, former leaders who have fled to Pakistan, but also often peasants who refuse an armed foreign presence, as in the Soviet era.
They want to defend their centuries-old and archaic traditions, even if they have been joined by jihadists, Pakistanis, Arabs, Uzbeks and Tajiks.
Tolerated, sometimes supported by local insurgents, the latter will be gone as western countries become more discreet.
The withdrawal of French troops from the base at Nijrab, which I watched from a hill planted with almond trees and financed by French loans, took place in an orderly manner.
The truck and tank convoys flown over by helicopters have reached Kabul without being attacked.
From the end of 2014 there will be no more influx of Taliban into Kabul.
Since their irresistible advance from 1994 to 1996, conditions have changed.
At that time, Kabul was empty and the country was engulfed in war due to the fighting of the various insurgent groups.
Their seizure of power was seen at the time as a kind of liberation and return to security.
Afghan women have paid the price for the obscurantism of farmers overwhelmed by the al-Qaeda organization, but their situation has not improved to this day.
Former mujahideen, the Afghan government and current Taliban share a common desire to keep women in a subordinate position.
The main figures of the anti-Soviet war returned to power in 2001.
They have turned into profiteers, seizing government land to sell for construction to refugees from Iran and Pakistan, capitalizing on massive American subcontracting.
They have brought themselves into disrepute, and most of them did not take part in the fighting themselves.
From what I&#39;ve heard in the campaigns, people want a government that isn&#39;t made up of thieves.
Many young people want to leave the country, as do those who have benefited from American grants: the flight of capital is considerable.
Young people are fed up with war and its ideologies.
During their exile in Iran or Pakistan they have had contact with the modern world and have enjoyed its benefits.
About 65% of the population is under the age of 25; Kabul now has 5 million inhabitants, which is one fifth of the total population.
In the cities, the state schools are full of both girls and boys.
Jobs will have to be made available to these young people, who do not want to return to the obscurantism of the old parties or to the corruption of certain leaders.
Everyone, including the armed parties, is obsessed with cell phones; television with its Turkish series depicting a modern world is watched everywhere.
An army now exists.
Will the authorities that will command it be considered legitimate?
Former commanders of the anti-Soviet struggle are already trying to restore the provincial militias, which will evade the power of the central government.
Afghanistan, the land of mountains with strong local identities, should have benefited from some decentralization along the lines of western nations, but by abolishing the office of prime minister that had existed since the 1964 constitution, the US wanted it to be a centralized state with a strong make presidential power.
President Karzaï does not want any foreign controls, especially on the occasion of the elections planned for April 2014.
However, his country has been dependent on foreign aid since the 1950s and long before that.
Industries have not been rebuilt, functioning dams are non-existent and important irrigation systems have not been repaired.
Everything is imported; nothing is produced apart from fruit and vegetables.
Priority is given to private initiative.
In a country devastated by 30 years of war, state control of infrastructure would have been necessary.
The rumor was spread that Afghanistan possessed immense natural resources.
This reinforces the impression that western countries were only there to seize it.
Mining is impossible without energy to process the iron or copper ore locally, or transportation to export it over the mountains.
The Chinese have almost abandoned the Mes Aynak copper mine, allowing international archaeologists (financed by the World Bank) to excavate the vast Buddhist site and remaining the province&#39;s main employers.
One day it will also be necessary for Afghanistan and Pakistan, on which largely depend for imports and exports, to restore normal relations.
The withdrawal of French combat troops was completed on November 20th.
The new cooperation agreement provides for the continuation of traditional aids: girls&#39; and boys&#39; high schools, institute of French at universities, French institute, cooperation in the military, legal, medical and agricultural fields, support for the archaeological delegation.
Since 2009, a &quot;Civil-Military Actions&quot; service of the Ministry of Defense (Cimic), which was discontinued in 2012, has carried out numerous community works and actions for the rehabilitation of agriculture in dozens of mountain villages and commissioned them by a small French non-governmental organization in order to trying to &quot;win hearts and minds&quot; and accomplish the impossible task of reconciling assists and offensive action.
These works, which required a large number of local workers, have helped to quell the uprising: irrigation, wells, drinking water, reforestation, fruit trees, soil protection and increase in agricultural land.
What souvenir are we leaving behind after military spending of two billion euros?
A much more modest budget will help improve the local living conditions, which are very harsh in these valleys, often located at an altitude of more than 2000 meters.
The embassy has received dozens of written requests for small-scale farming projects from municipalities in Kapisa province.
In order for the farmers to liberate themselves from the foreign-led insurgency, which they say they want, it would require the continuation of smaller, well-controlled and directly affecting civil aid in their favor.
A crowbar constitution in Egypt
It is a new poker game from President Mohammed Morsi.
As Egypt remains more divided than ever over the constitutional declaration temporarily granting it full powers, it has decided to gamble all on one card.
To everyone&#39;s surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would adopt his final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State granted this plenary two extra months to complete its work.
Egypt has been relying on a provisional text, which has been amended several times, for almost two years now, weakening institutional stability and creating legal confusion.
This new initiative has only further divided the country.
For his opponents, the president persists in his &quot;autocratic delirium&quot; by continuing to &quot;break his word&quot; and &quot;trespass on the law&quot;.
On the part of its supporters, assurances are given that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time, forcing the brothers to abandon their plan to explain the text section by section to the Egyptians.
It&#39;s also a way for the president to regain his public and democratic legitimacy as protests rage across the country.
According to an interview with the American newsreel Time, Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote well.
Especially since the Egyptian people are being presented with an ultimatum by resorting to a hasty vote: &quot;Either you vote for my draft or I keep unlimited powers&quot;, the latter should supposedly come to an end after the adoption of the constitution.
85 mostly Islamist members of this Constituent Assembly approved the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of Liberals did not comply with the request.
Shortly before the constitution was declared in mid-November, they backed down, believing they had been unable to get their views across.
Representatives of human rights organizations, religious minorities or civil society have acted in the same way.
To reach a quorum, 11 alternate members were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Not surprisingly, the articles were mostly passed unanimously.
Incidentally, commentators found it amusing that the only disagreement of the day...was expressed in the time for prayer, as some members of the panel felt that the Constituent Assembly pendulum clock was not accurate.
The text, which was approved yesterday evening, consists of 234 articles.
Finally, Article 2, which attracted all attention, remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution and states that &quot;the principles of Sharia are the principal source of law&quot;.
The Salafist parties, for which the establishment of Islamic law is an important demand, hoped to replace &quot;the principles&quot; with &quot;the rules&quot;, which would have made stricter application possible.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is a testament to their goodwill and respect for the other members of Egyptian society.
&quot;Hypocrisy&quot; retorted the liberals, who saw this as just a propaganda ploy.
Because according to them, the Islamization of the constitution takes place via other articles.
They pay particular attention to Article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, particularly with regard to verifying compliance with Sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because &quot;the people asked to comment have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy whatsoever.
Here one can see the first signs of a theocracy&quot;.
The Liberals&#39; fears are also fueled by the fact that the next rector of this university is likely to be far less moderate than the current one.
&quot;Currently, no concrete religious commitment can be identified.
With this constitution we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most of the jurists who worked on this text are not ulema, but academics, some of whom were trained in the French system,&quot; says Alexis Blouet, who is writing a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
However, he admits &quot;that there may be an ambiguity in relation to Article 220, since the terms used are borrowed from religious vocabulary.
One refers here in particular to the &quot;Fiqh&quot; [Islamic jurisprudence, ed. Red.].
And in the future, the question could be raised as to what extent civil judges are competent to rule on this.&quot;
In addition to its religious aspect, the text approved yesterday has been heavily criticized for the wide powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argue that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another point of contention: the powers of the army.
In line with the military&#39;s wish, defense budget scrutiny will not be submitted to Parliament but to a national defense council.
Likewise, there will be no ban on civil trials in military courts, as the human rights defense associations have called for.
The latter also share their concerns about the text, which they see as a threat to freedom.
The offense of blasphemy is maintained and insults are now banned, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, particularly for the press.
In addition, no more articles refer to the protection of women, stresses Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In her opinion, the only positive point is that Article 36 prohibits torture.
This word was not included in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian President had to speak on television last night, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists expect holy places, the navel of the world and a sea of brine
The Promised Land combines the glory of biblical truths, modern conveniences and unspoiled nature.
AIF gives you the top five reasons to visit Israel.
Bow to the holy places
Visit the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all who bathe in this river will receive God&#39;s blessings.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: turning water into wine at a wedding feast, walking on water, calming the storm at sea, and catching fish.
It was here that Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
Most sanctuaries, however, are found in Jerusalem.
Believers walk the Passion or the Way of the Cross of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The trail starts from the Roman fortress of Antonia, Pretorium, where the judgment was, and leads through the streets of the old city to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre, on Mount Golgotha, where the Crucifixion site, the Anointing Stone and the tomb of Jesus are located.
According to the Christian view, this is the navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
The Monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands on the spot where, according to Christian legend, grew the tree from which the cross for Jesus&#39; crucifixion was made.
Jerusalem is also home to the Jews&#39; holiest site - the Western Wall, the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in AD 70.
Traditionally, people of different faiths leave notes with wishes that are then fulfilled.
Take a journey to the top
The ruins of the fortress of Massada are the remains of the secret hiding place from enemies that Herod the Great built for his family in 25 AD.
They are located on a rock face in the mountains at 450 meters above sea level.
Only mountaineers can reach the ruins under their own steam.
For everyone else, a cable car takes you to this historic summit.
In the north of the country at an altitude of 1600 to 2040 meters is the famous Hermon ski area, which attracts countless tourists in the winter months.
From the base of the mountain you can get there by shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometers.
According to an old legend, pagan gods supposedly lived on the mountain top.
Visit unique museums
There are almost 300 museums in this country.
Not all of them can be visited in one trip.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be visited.
Among them is the Israel Museum not far from the Knesset (parliament).
Ancient Qumran manuscripts or Dead Sea Scrolls found in rock caves in the Judean Desert are kept there, as well as about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
The collection of works by the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso is on display there.
In Akko, you can visit the Al Basha Bath Museum, which houses several halls of old Turkish baths with sculptures of visitors and bath attendants of the time.
In Caesarea you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures by Dali and Rodin.
There are neither museum guides nor souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are generally refused.
The fifth museum, namely the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most harrowing chapters in history.
The most poignant section is the Children&#39;s Memorial, built to commemorate the 1.5 million children who perished in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
When entering the room it is completely dark.
stars twinkle.
And the names of the Jewish children and the countries in which they died resound.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
do something for your health
The three main resort areas of Israel lie on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
In each of the three locations there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Surprisingly, people bathe in the Red Sea even in the winter months, as the water temperature there does not drop below 21 °C and the air warms up to 23 °C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and is bathed all year round.
By the way, with a location of 417 meters below sea level, this unusual sea is the deepest sea in the world.
Its turquoise-blue water has a high salt content and thus even carries non-swimmers on the surface without any problems.
The surrounding landscape is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural brine) and medicinal mud, to treat skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and to soothe stressed nerves.
Touch the mysteries of antiquity
These secrets are hidden in the old town of Tel Aviv, namely the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
The famous sea route that connected Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia passed through this city.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to tradition, it was here that Noah built his ark, and it was here that Perseus rescued the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he lived a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists love to stroll through the narrow streets named after zodiac signs.
According to legend, Fortuna is kind to everyone who touches the walls in the alley with their zodiac sign.
In Jaffa, you can find newlywed couples from all over Israel and even other countries having photo ops.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can roam the Roman theater and conquer the Crusader fortress.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the most important city in Judea and the residence of the Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theater now hosts evening concerts and operas.
Tourist watch list
If you go to Israel, don&#39;t worry about your poor English skills: about 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
It is better to take the money on the trip not in euros, but in dollars, which can easily be exchanged for shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
Buses get you around the city most of the time, but Jerusalem also has an express tram and Haifa has the country&#39;s only six-station subway line, connecting the lower and upper cities.
Strictly speaking, it is an underground funicular.
A trip within the city costs 6 shekels regardless of the means of transport, which is enough for a trip of up to 1.5 hours including changes.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is observed in Israel on Saturdays.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed and public transport is at a standstill.
And on Sunday morning the working week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants, and inns, only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales, and dishes containing both dairy and meat products.
Instead, you can choose from a variety of mutton and beef dishes, soups and desserts (made with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus paste, various sauces, fried balls of mashed beans and peas (falafel), and fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
But there are many well-fed cats that roam the streets comfortably and unmolested.
In the evenings you can even see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
The cats like busy places and won&#39;t say no to treats.
Depending on the brand, a rental car costs between 37 dollars per day (Hyundai Getz) and 188 dollars (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Insurance is an additional $15 per day.
And bike rental costs 15 shekels per day.
Museum tickets cost an average of 30 shekels.
In numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most adventurers and those seeking relaxation came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the USA and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists came to the Promised Land, an increase of 51% compared to the same period in 2010, before the visa requirement was lifted on February 9, 2011.
&quot;The Great and Powerful&quot; leads to Moscow: migrants save money for language
While MPs and civil rights activists are discussing the benefits of the law on mandatory language tests for migrants, criminals are already trading in fake certificates
Every year 13 million foreign workers come to Moscow, Saint Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of them are the citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money to support the families who remain in their homeland.
On December 1, a law came into effect requiring every migrant worker to take a test proving knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this regulation only applies to migrants who want to work in the service sector, in municipal housing and in retail.
However, according to the federal migration authority, the tests should become mandatory for all guest workers in the future.
You have to pass not only language tests, but also tests on Russian history and the basics of legislation.
Language skills must be proven for both obtaining and extending the work permit.
Exceptions only apply to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
Also exempt from this law are people who obtained their educational certificates and diplomas before the breakup of the USSR in 1991.
Purpose, problems and protection of rights
All of the examination bodies will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute of Russian Language, Peoples&#39; Friendship University of Russia, Moscow State University, Saint Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
The migrants can take the tests in any city; more than 160 such centers have already been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Service on Migration.
Civil rights activists, on the other hand, repeatedly asked the following question in the press before the law came into force: What is the point of all this?
What changes does the requirement to show language skills bring, both for Russians and for guest workers?
Above all, counter the spokesman for the migration authorities, the aim is to reduce the number of forced labourers.
&quot;A lot of people are now talking about protecting the rights of migrant workers,&quot; says Viktor Sebelev, head of the Federal Migration Agency&#39;s office in Tajikistan.
However, their rights must be protected before they leave.
Only organized recruitment will solve 90% of foreign workers&#39; problems.
Problems are encountered by migrants without a job, education, language skills or a medical examination.
Sebelev is convinced that a future migrant who does not speak the language will inevitably encounter people with malicious intentions who, under the pretense of help, will put him in a dark, cramped barracks, where he will remain with dozens of his peers for months and 12 to 14 hours without food or documents will toil in the day.
We receive many complaints from our migrants.
&quot;You&#39;re promised one thing at home, and when you arrive you&#39;re cheated, your passports are taken away and you don&#39;t get the wages you promised,&quot; confirms the head of the main administration for labor migration at the Tajik Migration Agency, Tolib Zwaripov.
Don&#39;t scold, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who want to earn money in Russia admit that not only do they not speak the language of the destination country, but also that they can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault as the evil: only a few Turkmen, Uzbeks and Tajiks can even afford a decent primary education.
Because in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone to buy them decent clothes, shoes and school supplies.
As teenagers, these children immediately seize their first opportunity to earn money.
&quot;It&#39;s difficult without language skills,&quot; they admit.
&quot;You feel humiliated and inferior.&quot;
Civil rights activists emphasize the following important aspect of the law.
Only migrants with legal status have to take the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no examination and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, the majority of migrant workers continue to be in Russia illegally.
&quot;Welcome&quot; or &quot;No unauthorized access&quot;
Many migrants confirm that obtaining official status in Russia is not easy.
The reasons are bureaucratic hurdles and of course the language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: from 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
You can make a fake registration quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
Russian police officers know that most of our documents are forged and we are unregistered, and this leads to cases of extortion.
&quot;They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea,&quot; Tajik Umed Hushkadamov told journalists.
&quot;Don&#39;t shy away from the expense of false papers&quot;
Already on the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of the migrants could be forged.
Some fake certificates certifying the completion of the language test have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Service.
The fake papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not receive them for free: each migrant hoping to avoid the tests paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
That&#39;s more than twice the cost of the official test, which costs a migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Both public officials and civil rights activists agree that the most important immediate task is to protect the system from corruption so that the certificates cannot simply be bought.
For now, the authorities can only promise migrant workers who fail the test the first time that they will be given time for a basic language course.
In addition, newcomers without language skills are offered jobs in areas that do not require active communication with people.
Interior Ministry ignores illegal arms market
Extremely low proportion of legal firearms in criminal offences
The Russian Interior Ministry plans to tighten gun laws for private gun owners.
This is how the authorities are reacting to recent events: wounded in shootings at weddings and seven dead in the killing spree by Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov.
Police want to ban the carrying of non-lethal weapons in public and raise the age of firearm ownership from 18 to 21.
The proposal was supported by the chairman of the Duma Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption Irina Yarovaya and promised that amendments to the law on weapons will soon be submitted to the Duma.
Not everyone is happy that the Russian authorities want to solve the problems by &quot;tightening the screws&quot;.
An open letter was published on the Internet, the authors of which - representatives of various weapons associations - call on the authorities to refrain from &quot;senseless tightening&quot;.
The percentage of crimes involving registered weapons is very low, criminal lawyer Vasily Lesnikov told the BBC&#39;s Russian service.
According to Interior Ministry statistics, 142 crimes involving the use of registered weapons were committed during the six months of 2012, while a total of 1.168 thousand offenses were recorded for the same period.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that tightening the law on private gun owners will not prevent criminals from using the black market.
Currently, according to the authors, you can find any possible weapon in Moscow for little money.
Meanwhile, the Interior Ministry emphasizes that the proliferation of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from the factories to the officers
The guns find their way onto the black market through multiple channels.
There are five such main channels, says a former colonel Viktor Baranets, who worked for ten years in the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of a website that accepts gun orders
The first channel is the army, or rather, the military, that is, weapons stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
&quot;The weapons were stolen by both the Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves,&quot; says Baranez.
On the second channel come illegal weapons stolen from law enforcement officers by criminals.
Baranez explains that this includes weapons stolen both from police armories and directly from law enforcement officials.
Other illegally sold weapons come from military weapons stores.
Many military camps were subject to frequent explosions.
&quot;There is evidence that some cases involved arson to cover up the lack of weapons,&quot; says the former military man.
According to Baranez, gun manufacturers also contribute to the black market.
&quot;Nowadays there are countless private armaments factories that can&#39;t stand up to international competition and are therefore secretly dumping their weapons on the black market, for example in Moscow,&quot; reports the expert.
Another channel of the black market is smuggling.
A particularly large number of pistols and rifles come from poor countries such as Kyrgyzstan.
&quot;They have their own, sometimes artisan production there and a mafia that organizes smuggling,&quot; explains the former military man.
Where are the guns from?
Experts calculated the approximate share of each of the five channels in supplying the black market with illegal weapons.
In 2011, a report was written by the Center for Problem Analysis and State Administration.
The experts analyzed reports of the Ministry of Internal Affairs and the Federal Service for State Statistics, criminological literature and publicly available data on weapon-related portals.
According to investigators, most of the illegal weapons come from the army and law enforcement agencies.
Half of all guns on the black market got there through &quot;the fault of those responsible for their work related to guns,&quot; the report says.
According to the researchers&#39; data, 17% of weapons come from conflict zones, 14% are from thefts during weapons production, and 5% come from illegal excavations.
