We&#39;ve compared all of these and, although the review is ongoing, we&#39;ve found some very interesting differences. Generally speaking, the laws here are perhaps even a little &quot;stricter and more perfect&quot;, but the actual application in Germany is better in some parameters.
This confirms that it is not enough to keep setting new and more precise rules. One must also deal with the actual application of the law.
How can the project help you? What does this project mean for you?
It is precisely such joint control that could help us to stop constantly trying to perfect the laws and lower and balance thresholds when this does not appear to be having a particularly positive effect.
Profitability means acquiring an item at a reasonable price (which is not always the lowest price) and excluding unlawful enrichment or even criminal acts.
But lowering thresholds for orders does not guarantee that we will achieve this goal.
It may even be the case that in this way we just burden the system with excessive &quot;paperwork&quot; and those looking for loopholes in the system have it much easier to exploit the system than if the thresholds stayed higher.
They talk about the problems in the practical implementation of the Czech Public Procurement Act.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there a similar authority here as our NKÚ, or does the system work differently?
As far as the authorities are concerned, the German counterpart to the NKÚ is the Federal Audit Office, which has a similar structure to ours and also has a board that is only formed slightly differently. In principle, however, both authorities work in a similar way.
The competences are also comparable to a certain extent, although Germany is a federal state, which means that these audit offices also exist in the individual federal states - this is where the German system differs from ours.
The BRH is only allowed to control federal funds, which corresponds to our state funds.
Public funds, which are managed by the districts and municipalities in our country, are subject to the control of the state audit offices there.
As for German legislation, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I would be reluctant to compare this without specific information. Nevertheless, Germany is often cited as a role model in certain respects, although one certainly cannot say that Germany is better in everything.
Is that perhaps because the examiners are better there?
Definitely not, but as I said: I don&#39;t particularly like such comparisons.
It should also be noted that those countries that are role models for us also have problems to contend with.
Otherwise they wouldn&#39;t benefit from working with our agency, would they?
As far as Czech legislation is concerned, how important was the amendment to the Public Procurement Act for your authority, do you already feel any impact?
In view of the fact that this amendment has only been in force for a short time, it has not yet had any effect on our tests.
Since our controls take place afterwards, you have to expect a certain delay here.
So far, we have felt the effects more in the preparatory phase of future controls - for example, we introduced the new control instrument &quot;Detection of risks of inefficiency&quot; and used it to examine and analyze almost 14,000 public contracts - the changes will of course have an effect here, as the threshold values change, the conditions for certain types of tenders have been modified, etc
Do you see the passage of this law as positive, or will the system be burdened with further bureaucracy?
I think that this law is definitely a step in the right direction and I hope that this assumption will be confirmed.
However, the problem can arise that the rules become &quot;stricter&quot; and can no longer be observed.
Already under the previous rules, the persons subjected to an audit are accountable to the promoter (for example, in the case of a regional policy operational programme, the regional council) such that any non-compliance with the procurement law amounts to a breach of budgetary discipline.
But does it then make sense to make the law even stricter?
I don&#39;t think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse the system, and not penalize those who have made a formal error that does not affect actual decision-making.
Such a system only puts even more pressure on the bureaucracy.
Where is the way out here?
First of all, let&#39;s say which way is not effective.
The Prime Minister recently said that the ODS would not bother entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called &quot;black system&quot; - what does that mean exactly?
Is the black system now forbidden or allowed?
A law must still be valid, and if something is forbidden by law, then the head of the government cannot simply come and hinder the work of the control office, whose duty it is to monitor compliance with the law.
He can say, &quot;We&#39;ll change the law and allow it,&quot; but he can&#39;t say we&#39;re pretending it&#39;s nothing.
The Public Procurement Act contains relatively strict rules about the formal execution of certain processes - and this is also correct for the protection of public competition.
On the other hand, it is also tragic when the bidder with the best offer is excluded solely because of formal errors.
The law will never be perfect, but it has to be applied correctly - and that&#39;s what I think we&#39;re lacking.
