Šimon Ornest: We want to collect positive energy at our concerts
What do you think about the end of the world happening in less than a month?
This is one of those catastrophe reports that we humans like to jump on.
With our band The Tap Tap we rather make fun of it and say that we are the only band in the world that can collect enough positive energy to stop or prevent the end of the world.
In December you will also realize a unique project with three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you introduce our readers to the project in more detail?
It&#39;s a nationwide fundraiser that we&#39;ve been planning for two years.
For this we want to use the marketing potential of the Mayan calendar, which is predicted to end on December 21 at 11:10 in the morning.
The day before, ie December 20, three concerts will take place simultaneously in Prague, Brno and Ostrava from 9:00 p.m.
The concerts are scheduled to end around the time that the Mayan calendar ends on the Pacific island of Kiribati, which is 12 hours ahead of us in a time zone.
Who came up with this idea?
Originally by me, we then developed the idea together with our graphic designer Honza Augusta.
We not only want to collect enough positive energy to prevent the end of the world, but we also want to think together with the public about the state in which we will hand this world over to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar, we have also developed a unique collection of shoes, t-shirts, bags and keychains against the end of the world, which people can also support us by purchasing via www.e-tap.cz.
The band The Tap Tap, together with other performers, also recorded the so-called anthem against the end of the world entitled &quot;End of the World&quot;.
The anthem is already very popular on YouTube. Will it also be heard at the benefit concerts?
Of course, and at the very end, provided that everything works out and the end of the world doesn&#39;t happen...
The anthem is to be sung simultaneously by all performers at all three concerts.
In addition, the anthems will be broadcast live together in a direct broadcast on Czech television.
The text of the hymn comes from Tomáš Hanák, who also plays the main character of Jesus in the video clip, Xindl X also sings along...
How did you come to work with both of them?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, which is related to the fact that we organize many charity events and concerts...
We try to involve these people intensively in our projects.
It turned out that most of them are interested in working with us and enjoy it.
What purpose does the proceeds of the concerts against the end of the world benefit?
For the establishment of the barrier-free educational center Studeo, on which we have been working for six years together with the Tap Association at the Jedlička Institute.
The students of the Jedlička Institute are regularly supervised by lecturers who help them with various free time activities.
Since the students themselves do not have the means to visit the lecturers, we would like to help them in this way.
As part of the completion of the Jedlička Institute, a separate building is to be built, which we will then move into with this project.
Several groups and performers perform at each concert.
What criteria did you use to select them?
We wanted to put together a program that would appeal to all generations including children.
In Prague, for example, Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý will perform.
You can find out more on the website www.kpks.cz.
Are similar &quot;major events&quot; planned for the future?
In May we will perform at the Prague Spring for the first time, and we are preparing an interesting program with interesting guests for this concert as well.
Next year we would also like to perform at the Czech House in New York, and personally - while we&#39;re in the USA - I would also like to combine this with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your plans abroad are not exactly small, you have already performed in Madrid, Brussels, London and Moscow.
However, The Tap Tap is a group made up of people with disabilities.
How do you manage these trips logistically and organizationally?
It&#39;s not as bad as it first appears.
Five of our members are wheelchair users, which means that the wheelchairs must be transported in the luggage compartment. Of course, we also have to carry a lot of instrument cases and other luggage with us...
Nevertheless, it has always worked without any problems so far, ČSA and British Airways were always very well prepared for us, which sometimes surprised me.
Even in Moscow, where we recently went, there were no problems.
Through your trips abroad, you have a comparison of how accessibility is in the individual countries, how disabled people are treated there, etc.
How have you experienced these things so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities where everything works better than here, we in Russia were witnesses to the fact that everything in the East is still in its infancy.
Compared to Prague, Moscow is absolutely not handicapped accessible. There it is still unusual for someone in a wheelchair to walk around the city center alone.
It is not even a matter of course there that a wheelchair user is allowed to enter the elevator, for example.
Fortunately, there are also associations that try to draw attention to the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what respect do we have to catch up with the more developed countries?
There are still many things we are lagging behind on...
However, it should also be noted that an improvement in the situation always depends on the efforts of those affected.
In London and Madrid, it is absolutely normal for people with severe disabilities to be able to move around independently in public spaces, go to museums, use toilets, etc.
However, it is not exactly common for a large group of disabled people to actively participate in social events there. With the band The Tap Tap we are a little ahead of the west!
Public respect and accessibility are one thing, but it&#39;s not until a major athlete, artist, actor, politician or lawyer joins our ranks that things will really start to change.
So far, these have only been isolated cases of particularly strong-willed personalities.
The Tap Tap is very popular these days. But if we go back a few years, what motivated you to form a band in 1998?
At that time I started as a tutor at the Jedlička Institute, where I met many young people who were interested in doing something intensively.
And since I&#39;m a musician myself and play the saxophone, among other things, I founded a music club together with a colleague.
Well, over time, as our moderator Láďa Angelovič likes to say, it got a bit out of control (laughs).
But the band only became known in the last few years, or am I wrong?
It&#39;s true that working with well-known singers has helped us; we have also started to actively promote ourselves.
We have become aware that if you achieve something and this cannot be seen from the outside, your own achievement does not exist in a certain sense.
Thanks to the EU funding, we can also hire good editors, high-quality equipment and the like. afford.
Was your goal to make it this far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning I felt the potential to do things differently.
In show business today, one often copies the other.
This is logical in its own way, since anything new is viewed with caution and accepted only after a long period of time.
There are few things that are truly unique, and I daresay Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression that the viewer usually has is, of course, pity; it&#39;s only natural...
But that pity is totally unnecessary because people with disabilities are not lonely and abandoned beings for whom we need to pity.
They are people who can live a full life and develop if they have the means to do so.
I always say that when people with disabilities succeed in something, it&#39;s not just a step forward for themselves, but for society as a whole.
Was it also helpful for this success that you are a strict boss, as many people say?
If you want to do something well, you can&#39;t make any compromises in many things and you have to demand a certain discipline.
I think this is completely normal.
Some come to us with romantic ideas, and when they find that they have twice-a-week rehearsals, go through preparatory phases, and spend a lot of time on concert tours, many quickly lose their enthusiasm.
But that&#39;s how it works everywhere, in every band that wants to work seriously and achieve something.
Currently, The Tap Tap has twenty members.
How many of them were there from the beginning, ie since 1998?
Only one: Láďa Angelovič.
We are an open group. People come and go. You can&#39;t prevent that.
Anyone with the will and the desire to participate is always welcome.
