Poland and Space.
Last week, at a Council of Ministers meeting of the member countries of the European Space Agency (ESA), Poland became the twentieth member of this space agency. This makes Poland the second member country from the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became an ESA member on November 12, 2008).
Poland started close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
Of course, Poland&#39;s journey into space began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish cosmos enthusiasts were involved in space travel, although they were not always understood.
I would like to remind you, for example, of the lecture by A. Šternfeld on December 6, 1933 at the Warsaw Observatory, where the author presented ideas from his pioneering work &quot;Entrance to Cosmonautics&quot;.
However, the ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the audience cold, and years later Šternfeld still remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won the Prix REP-Hirsch donated by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch for &quot;Entrance to Cosmonautics&quot;.
dr Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space travel.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski&#39;s contribution to the development of space travel, which is recognized worldwide, was recognized by the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the moon was named after him.
As early as 1925, a railway handcar was built in Poland, for which rocket propulsion was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the design and the details of this project remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket was to be used to launch or to brake the handcar.
The information on this comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began dealing with rocket-propelled projectiles.
The research work was carried out by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
It can be seen from the surviving documents that the research had progressed to the stage of practical testing.
The research was then of course interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937, the design of a photoelectric rocket launcher by Ing. Rohoziński appeared in the specialized press, and the following year the work &quot;Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza&quot; by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky was published.
Both projects dealt with the military use of rocket propulsion.
Shortly before the war, all projects on the military use of rocketry were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy).
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of activity, its work was terminated by the beginning of the war.
More articles on space travel appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The first mention of this company is in the November 1954 issue of Problemy magazine, in which four extensive articles are dedicated to space travel.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal to create a space company.
At that time, the first satellite technology projects were already underway, and it was foreseeable that space exploration would have a future.
From the outset in 1956, the Polish Space Agency (PTA) tried to join the International Space Federation founded in 1951, and in fact the PTA became a full member as early as autumn 1956.
The following year, the first PTA Chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became Deputy Chairman of the International Space Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been instrumental in the development of the highly successful Meteorological Rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, and the first launch was on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight altitude of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and weighed not quite 5 kg.
An improved version, the RM-1A, was later built, and in 1959 flight tests with the RM-2 two-stage rocket began in the Błędów Desert.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the rocket RM-34 should reach a flight altitude of up to 14.5 km and be used for observing high-altitude winds.
In 1962, however, further development was discontinued.
The Meteor 1 rocket, developed between 1962 and 1965, was the successor to the first RM rockets.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the launch weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types of this rocket were developed (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed from each other in the size of the space for carrying scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a transport compartment with a capacity of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1B - 0.34 liters, and Meteor-1C - 0.62 liters.
The maximum flight altitude was 37 km for all three types.
In 1965-1968, the Meteor 2 rocket was developed at the Aviation Institute, the first flight tests of which began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a takeoff weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a 10 kg payload to an altitude of approximately 60 km.
After that, versions Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth noting Poland&#39;s entry into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, which was followed two years later by the establishment of a national COSPAR committee.
Poland also participated in space exploration with Soviet satellites as part of the Interkosmos program, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after the Czech Vladimír Remek.
Repealing the Community Works Act is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court overturned the Law on Community Works.
This decision provoked lively public debate.
It is certainly interesting to look at the problem from a broader perspective.
The liberally oriented economic systems in the EU and in the globalized world are based on the principle of unregulated economic competition.
Ultimately, this means that the individual economies are in constant conflict with each other.
This is due to the principle of free trade and the free, unrestricted movement of private capital, which goes hand in hand with rampant financial speculation.
Price tensions arise due to large differences in the value of labor (wages).
This term refers to a situation in which the manufacturer attempts to compete economically by importing cheaper goods, &quot;undercutting&quot; the competition in order to gain a larger share of the market and increase profits.
On a large scale, this means for most companies to move their production abroad, to buy cheaply there, or to go out of business. The result is high unemployment in countries with comparably high labor costs.
Since private capital bears no social responsibility and thus no responsibility for the unemployment it causes, government spending necessarily increases.
This situation is exacerbated by the fact that the entrepreneurs are absolutely unwilling to pay their taxes and thereby compensate for the economic and social damage they have caused to society as a whole.
This situation is well known, so concrete statistics are superfluous at this point.
The ruthless practice of private capital creates a situation in individual economies in which governments are forced to compete with one another in order to artificially lower the social standard of their own population and thereby attract foreign capital.
In other words, governments hand over their own people to private capital, regardless of the social consequences.
This is reflected in particular in changes to applicable laws.
The aim of these measures is to force the population to accept the dictates of private capital, especially in the area of wages.
This happens on the one hand through economic coercion in the case of long-term unemployment, on the other hand through the curtailment of workers&#39; rights.
The result is growing poverty and widening gaps between rich and poor.
In Germany, for a number of years, there have been public food distribution points for the poor who are no longer able to support themselves through their own work.
The number of those affected is already in the millions.
In the course of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, there are regularly cases in which employees receive such low wages that the state has to increase their income to the subsistence level.
Such a scandal was also uncovered in the case of auxiliary workers employed in the German Bundestag.
The austerity measures of virtually all southern EU states will undoubtedly result in the same condition, with people being forced to emigrate under the pressure of a catastrophic drop in their social standard (as was the case in the 19th century) or for starvation wages on the Starving on the fringes of society and hoping that at some point private investment capital will flow into the country.
The question that naturally arises here is where does this capital come from?
When it comes from another EU country, poverty just moves from one country to another; or there is no capital at all, because in China, India, Brazil, Turkey, Morocco or Egypt or in Africa in general, employees work for a fraction of European wages.
This affects all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media claim ad nauseam that the state is not allowed to contribute capital to its own economy and that a planned economy leads to economic catastrophe.
Private capital narrow-mindedly insists that the state should not intervene in the economy.
But then you have to ask yourself whether private capital influences or even directs politics and thus the entire state in its own selfish sense.
Here is the unequivocal answer: Yes.
The proof of this is the existence of a practically omnipotent lobby that is ubiquitous in all states.
The result is a desperate situation in the area of corruption, mutual advantage, a legislation where practically everything is punishable but nothing is punishable.
In Germany, the situation is such that, due to a lack of funds, a state ministry commissions private legal companies, which are closely linked with industry, to draft legislation.
These bills are then passed in the Bundestag.
All violence then no longer emanates from the people, as proclaimed by Western constitutions, but from powerful financial groups that put their own interests first.
Apparently, the liberal democracies are quickly getting into a situation like that described by Appian in his work on the crisis of the Roman republic in the time of Caesar and Pompey: &quot;The state had long been in the process of decay, and the offices were filled by force.
In exchange for bribes, by illegally obtaining advantages or with stone and sword.
Corruption ran rampant and the people went to the polls with already bought votes&quot; ... &quot;People of character did not run for office, so as a result of this decline the state had no consul for eight months&quot; ... &quot;It was already beginning to really talk about the fact that the only medicine in this difficult situation is autocracy and that a strong man must be elected&quot;... Appian was thinking of Pompeius, but the strong man was finally Caesar, who implemented democracy permanently replaced autocracy.
As it turns out, today&#39;s society, just like in antiquity, is based on the ruthless preference for one&#39;s own advantage without paying attention to the interests of society as a whole.
By its very nature, private capital is incapable of recognizing and implementing the benefits for society as a whole.
The result, now as then, is an unprecedented decadence of the elites, which make no attempt at deeper reforms.
We must therefore look for the cause of the rise of fascism and communism in the ruthless liberalization of the economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
As things stand today, the demise of these regimes in favor of liberal democracies can be seen as a certain pause, with the next round already looming.
What is particularly catastrophic is the fact that today&#39;s elites are faced with the possible future loss of hundreds of thousands of lives, the humanitarian and social catastrophes we are already witnessing today, and the crimes against humanity as we know them from ancient and modern history , face in complete ignorance.
Repealing the Community Works Act is not a solution here, at least not a permanent one.
Under the pressure of global and European economic competition, the Czech Republic will be forced to continue looking for ways to push down the social level of the population.
This trend is therefore systemic.
The only solution is targeted political and social reforms that increase state capital participation in the economy, increase citizens&#39; influence in government, and weaken the monopoly of private capital in society in favor of the state.
