The movie Argo: Call Hollywood when the going gets tough
In November 1979, a mob of demonstrating Islamist students occupied the US Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
For their release, they demanded the extradition of the deposed Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the United States after the revolution, which had maintained patronage over his regime for decades.
There was no positive way out of this situation for the American government - it could not afford to jettison the shah, as this would have massively damaged the confidence of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, it was unable to secure the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution resulted in the installation of a theocratic regime.
It was a severe blow to the reputation of the United States, and the subsequent hostage rescue fiasco only made matters worse.
The captured diplomats were eventually released after 444 days after negotiations were mediated by the Algerian government.
The fate of the hostages provoked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment at home.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter&#39;s defeat by Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
Director/actor Ben Affleck&#39;s film Argo describes an episode of this story that gave the US a small partial victory.
Immediately before the embassy was occupied, six embassy employees managed to escape.
This ended after numerous complications at the Canadian Ambassador&#39;s residence.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to bring the refugees out of Iran; Helping them do so was an extravagant story to obscure their true identities - they were traveling on Canadian passports disguised as members of a film crew supposedly visiting locations for a sci-fi film in the country.
combination of genres
Developed by &quot;exfiltration&quot; expert Tony Mendez, the plan also required Hollywood cooperation.
In order for the cover to be believable, articles about this film project appeared in trade journals, press conferences were held, and the fictional production company had a real office.
The details of this operation have long been kept secret. The film is based on the memoirs of Tony Mendez.
Affleck&#39;s film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand it is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time it is also a so-called &quot;caper movie&quot;, ie the story of a successful feat such as the film Ocean&#39;s Eleven.
As a result, the mood levels in the film alternate - on the one hand the documentary scenes from Tehran (in the title sequence iconic contemporary photographs are shown, and there are no major differences in the film version of the same situations either).
On the other hand, there are the casual passages from Hollywood, which come across as ironic and slightly exaggerated.
And then there are the scenes from CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits at the conference table, in the hallways, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has made a remarkable new start to his career with this film.
A ridiculed actor has become a respectable director, and even as an actor he is no longer the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the crime drama Gone Baby Gone (2007) and the thriller City Without Mercy (2010).
It&#39;s also Affleck&#39;s first film not set in the director&#39;s native Boston.
The feel for the atmosphere of the place was one of the characteristics that set the director&#39;s previous films above the Hollywood standard.
However, Affleck also shows that flair in Argo, where Tehran is &quot;played&quot; by Canada.
The film&#39;s best scenes are set in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that actually took place - the opening sequence of the storming of the embassy is impressive in its clarity, while still conveying the sense of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when somewhere once the story moves.
Affleck and his team achieve a similar effect with fictional scenes (the fake film staff in a bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story doesn&#39;t actually offer many exciting scenes in a cinematic sense.
But he works quite successfully with what little he has, sometimes helping out with reality - which doesn&#39;t always come across as elegant (the scenes in which the impending crisis at the airport in Tehran is averted by a phone call in America, or the chase on the runway, seem a bit artificial).
Argo&#39;s weakness is its overly wide spread, driven by the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman, while charming in their roles as Hollywood staffers, deserve more space for their characters, and they&#39;re far from alone in the film.
As a result, Affleck&#39;s film loses some of its appeal. It&#39;s a movie to watch with some interest, while appreciating the design and retro style reminiscent of a 70&#39;s thriller.
However, it is difficult for him to arouse enthusiasm.
However, it is sufficient as a reminder of a piece of history that is still alive in a certain way today and as proof of how exaggerated the ideas of the omnipotent and omniscient secret services are.
Balloon inflation, banana and circus guidelines
The server www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which conducts an annual survey about the most absurd bank fees, decided this year to organize the competition &quot;Most absurd regulation or idea from the EU workshop&quot;.
&quot;We got this idea from the plan recently put forward by the EU to introduce a 40% quota of women in the management of large European companies,&quot; Patrik Nacher, who is in charge of organizing this survey, told the Právo newspaper.
Among the absurdities nominated is, for example, the judgment of the European Court of Justice on the harmonization of insurance tariffs for men and women.
Until then, women enjoyed an advantage in life insurance because they objectively posed less risk to insurance companies.
&quot;Other incredible ideas from the EU workshop can be nominated until the end of this year.
The actual vote will then take place by the end of February 2013,&quot; said Nacher.
The controversial EU regulations include the mandatory addition of bioethanol to fuels, which is harmful to nature as a result, the ban on reliable mercury thermometers simply because they contain a relatively small amount of this hazardous substance, or the directive on the size of chicken coops , because of which eggs became significantly more expensive this year.
The de facto ban on the use of the term &quot;butter spread&quot; and the ban on the sale of conventional light bulbs have also received criticism in the past.
Bananas must be 14 cm long
The EU apparatus often makes decisions under pressure from this or that lobby from trade and industry, whose demands in Brussels are usually represented by one or more member countries (the Czech Republic, for example, is currently trying to enforce the demands of Czech banks with the threat of a veto) .
Lobby interests were also behind the fact that bananas of the highest trading class in the EU must be at least 14 cm long and must not have any &quot;curvature anomalies&quot;.
The European Commission defended itself by arguing that it was merely harmonizing inconsistent national standards that would hamper trade.
The norms for fruit and vegetables have already been softened by the EU against the opposition of some countries, pointing out that the previous guidelines would lead to food wastage.
A possible candidate for winning this poll is last year&#39;s EU regulation requiring balloons to be sold with a warning that children under the age of eight are not allowed to inflate the balloon without adult supervision.
The EU referred to an American study that, according to balloons, is the leading cause of death by suffocation in children.
A similar restriction already applies to children up to the age of 14 when using fairground toads.
Strange things happen at home, too
A directive that affects European officials themselves is also relatively absurd - anyone who holds an official position in the EU is not allowed to use the term Macedonia because of the sensitivity of the topic to Greece and has to say FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia) instead .
The Bankovnípoplatky.com server, in cooperation with the Laissez Faire Association of Liberal Economists, nominated, in addition to the above absurdities, the EU regulation on the size of food stocks on the territory of a member country.
The EU thus set the maximum volume of food stocks that could be on the territory of the Czech Republic on the day we joined the EU.
The Czech Republic, for example, then exceeded the specified volume for canned mushrooms, for which we were threatened with a large fine.
The poll organizers were also impressed by the idea that certain countries should be paid for not having a sea, or by the idea of giving grants for grant applications.
Of course, these ideas did not come from Brussels, but from Prague.
&quot;We are handicapped by not having a sea.
We will apply for reimbursement from the EU,&quot; declared the then Agriculture Minister Jaroslav Palas (ČSSD) in autumn 2004.
As an argument, he argued that the grain harvest was very high and the state stocks were overflowing as a result of the so-called intervention purchases.
Since the Czech Republic has another way to seaports, according to Palas, the EU should pay us hundreds of millions of euros.
In the end, the European Commission was so accommodating to the Czech Republic that it organized a tender for the purchase of grain from countries that have no access to the sea.
The Ministry for Regional Development, headed by Minister Pavel Němec (US-DEU), offered the municipalities funding for applications for funding, specifically funds for submitting applications for funding to Brussels.
EU: Bizarre regulations are the exception
Although regulations are easily the target of criticism in the member states, some experts believe that the EU&#39;s efforts to regulate and thus also to improve the effectiveness and development of the entire European Union deserve more recognition.
According to these experts, a more serious problem is the EU funding for projects that have absolutely nothing in common with the deepening of European integration, but which were enforced by individual member states during budget negotiations.
The fact that the Czech Republic, like other member countries, has to fight in Brussels for the right to use specific designations of traditional products, and does not always win this fight, also arouses emotions in this country.
After a six-year struggle with Germany and Austria, the Czech Republic was able to defend the name &quot;Olomoucké tvarůžky&quot;, the Inländerrum (Tuzemský rum), whose tradition dates back to the 19th century, but our producers had to rename it &quot;Tuzemák&quot;.
The designation rum may only be used for products made from sugar cane distillate, not for products made from sugar beet.
The official list of products registered in the EU, together with the world-famous feta and gorgonzola cheeses, Lübeck marzipan and Parma ham, now also include Karlovy Vary rusks, carp from Pohořelice and Třeboň, and hops from Saaz.
Pardubice gingerbread or Hořice rolls can boast of an EU brand.
