The MVRDV architects prove that real adventures are not only in the mind - with the example of Spijkenisse and the recently built book hill - 2 photos
&quot;I think the building is funny, it looks futuristic and finally there is something interesting to see again,&quot; says Lisette Verhaig, a passer-by on the side of the road.
And Stefan Spermon, IT technician in a nearby large company, says: &quot;Yes, it&#39;s nice, the house.&quot;
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
All have Internet, iPad and e-books.
Nobody goes to one of those old-style libraries voluntarily anymore, do they?
Spijkenisse, a dormitory town outside the gates of Rotterdam that hardly needs to be visited, is a strange record holder.
The 80,000-inhabitant municipality has the lowest education rate in the entire Netherlands.
In order to counteract this stupid circumstance, it was decided a few years ago to contribute to general education and to recreate the seven fictitious bridges that are shown on the euro notes as nicely painted reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the education offensive was limited.
And so the city fathers realized that there was only one way to master the statistics: a library was needed!
Winy Maas from the Rotterdam architects&#39; office MVRDV, master of daring bar charts and producer of funny, often cynical buildings, took the matter with his usual composure and appeared at the competition hearing in 2003 with five books under his arm and a grin on his face.
And while the jury was still looking around in amazement and shrugging their shoulders, the cheeky Maas stacked his exquisite souvenirs according to size into a pyramid and ended his actionist-based speech with the words: &quot;Dear municipality!&quot;
So that&#39;s it, my suggestion for the Spijkenisse Book Mountain, for the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain was heaped up.
It is part of a revitalization project that also includes an underground car park, supermarket, post office and a few adjoining residential and terraced houses with a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, the book mountain was awarded the second prize &quot;Best Library of NL 2012&quot;.
The project has also been nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
This means that the faceless small-town retort, which until then had nothing more to offer than a post-modern pedestrian zone and a stunned ugly town hall, behind whose white facades one would be inclined to suspect a dairy factory, is richer by a piece of contemporary architecture.
Above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in the history of its existence.
The long way to the book
The first impression: Eldorado of books under a cheese dome.
Although there is a lift that leads through the middle of the mountain massif, the true joys of space and reading are revealed when you climb the topography on foot.
The interior, which is glazed all around, is bright and clear, the burned clinker floor and the elegant street lamps speak the language of a public city square unmistakably.
The urban ambience is perfect.
One is already on the lookout for park benches, dogs and boys and girls playing soccer.
And everywhere books, books, books.
&quot;Usually the bookshelves are along the facade, and in the middle is a big, dark room that&#39;s mostly uncomfortable and impersonal,&quot; says Winy Maas.
We turned the classic room configuration on its head and turned the reading area inside out.
The interior of the book hill is cleverly used: in the middle are offices, an internet library, a chess club, an environmental center and a building services center.
The black bookshelves, which are sometimes wall coverings, sometimes parapets, sometimes banisters, are a particular delight.
The look, feel and smell are alien.
Even die-hard architects and civil engineers shake their heads at the unknown building material.
&quot;We wanted to work with recycled materials here,&quot; explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, when asked by Standard.
And so one day we came across a suitable waste product from agriculture in a Friesland farm.
For many years, a millimeter-thin plastic fleece has been used as a root pad in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands.
This is cheap and time efficient.
The thin textile lasts for a season or two, after which it is ready for bulky waste.
For the library, the fleece was pressed - for the first time in this quantity - into panels four centimeters thick.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called Landbouwplastic (KLP) discolours into a dark, homogeneous, resilient material that smells a bit like a new car and a bit like sports shoes.
After 105 steps you have reached the summit.
At the end of the almost 500-metre hike, you will not only be rewarded with a fantastic view of the city in the literature café, but also with Dutch croquettes and potted ficus trees.
They create atmosphere, but above all the right humidity in the literary mountains.
Donations for the new soul
&quot;You wouldn&#39;t believe it, but despite the many glass surfaces, this house is a showcase project in terms of ecology,&quot; says Trouborst.
It is heated and cooled with geothermal energy.
Although the book hill is under a glass dome, the sun only shines briefly into the interior, even on sunny days.
The wide laminated wood beams, which are perpendicular to the glass facade, serve as shade and absorb a large part of the solar radiation.
The indoor climate is very pleasant.
Fully automatic roller blinds do the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the initial skeptic from the IT industry, has already ventured into the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was also there.
And also the TCM teacher Cynthia Bogarde, who even describes the Boekenberg as Spijkenisse&#39;s &quot;long overdue soul&quot;.
The reason: At the opening a few weeks ago, every resident was invited to donate a book from their personal inventory.
This should initially fill the optical gaps in the library, which is not yet fully stocked - currently 70,000 pieces.
The concept worked.
The shelves are filled to the brim.
&quot;Nothing is worse than a half-empty library,&quot; says architect Winy Maas.
&quot;I think thanks to our invitation, every resident now has some sort of relationship with this new home.
Everyone knows his book is part of this building.
Even if it&#39;s just for show.
MVRDV has thus succeeded in the supreme discipline that is known in technical jargon as identity formation.
Spijkenisse wrote literary history.
No matter how young and uneducated she may be.
This is finally a starting point for identity.
