&quot;Brand protection&quot; in China: When Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani is a world-renowned brand, as is Polo Ralph Lauren.
But what is Armani Polo?
This is a name that is officially registered in China, but has nothing to do with the original company.
Nevertheless, it enjoys protection as long as the actual namesake does not complain.
And even then it is not clear whether they will be right.
&quot;It is becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China,&quot; says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing law firm who specializes in property right infringements in the Far East.
A new case lands on my desk every week.
A few additional letters are enough for the imitators to register their trademarks.
So Gucci simply becomes Lu-Gucci, instead of Prada you can enter Prada-Kny.
German companies are also legally copied in this way, such as the sporting goods manufacturer Puma.
Pattloch opens a folder with entries from the trademark office in Beijing.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company registered the Zegna DF Puma trademark there, an artificial name that was also used by the Ermenegildo Zegna fashion house.
It is well known that the Chinese are world champions in copying and infringing on intellectual property.
In the big cities there are multi-story department stores that sell almost exclusively fakes.
But Pattloch&#39;s cases are different: on behalf of his clients, he takes action against Chinese companies being officially granted the right by the trademark office to use a designation that is already protected elsewhere.
The Chinese call this &quot;Bang Mingpai&quot;, a passenger brand.
The word is based on &quot;Bang Dakuan&quot;.
This means women who lure rich men.
The Chinese authorities are not aware of any guilt
&quot;It&#39;s bad for business, you have to fight it,&quot; demands Pattloch.
&quot;The brand is diluted, the unique position disappears, the image damage is enormous.&quot;
The financial losses and the process costs for the affected industries run into the millions, especially for expensive flagship products.
According to the market research company CLSA, China is the third largest market for luxury goods and the fastest growing with a volume of 15 billion euros a year.
But deleting dubious entries in the trademark register is difficult to achieve and costs money.
The process can drag on for up to nine years, with an uncertain outcome.
Pattloch reports on cases in which the court dismissed lawsuits because the name in question had become &quot;market reality&quot; after a long period of time.
If the plaintiff is unlucky, he even has to pay the plagiarist money because he infringes his trademark in China, says Pattloch.
Sometimes the law of the jungle rules here.
Famous cases also affect graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a legal battle with construction equipment manufacturer Sany, the company that recently acquired German concrete pump maker Putzmeister.
The Chinese are therefore still allowed to use an emblem that resembles the Mercedes star.
Volvo buyer Geely originally used a blue and white logo reminiscent of BMW; the dispute was settled, Geely had to change it.
Fashion maker Lacoste lost in China to Hong Kong and Singapore imitators who made the famous crocodile look the other way.
The Chinese authorities are not aware of any guilt.
The trademark office CTMO in Beijing admits that there were bottlenecks there in 2010 due to insufficient staff and space.
In the past year, however, the &quot;emergency situation in the work process has returned to normal&quot;.
The number of unprocessed objection cases has fallen by 22 percent.
Almost 57,000 such cases have been closed, 75 percent more than in the previous year.
Nevertheless, 81,500 objections are still waiting to be settled in the office.
It costs a lot to counteract this
As so often in China, the numbers are impressive.
Last year, the CTMO received more than 1.4 million applications for trademark protection, almost a third more than in 2010.
That is a record and means that China tops the list of new registrations around the world for the tenth consecutive year, the agency said.
This also applies to the stock of all valid trademarks, a total of 5.5 million pieces.
In 2011, 1.8 billion yuan in fees were taken.
Put simply, this means that each registration costs an average of 1,280 yuan or 160 euros.
Tackling this costs a lot, as the case of the German family company Freudenberg shows.
The company has been fighting a Chinese plagiarist for more than seven years.
The Germans were able to get his illegal manufacture of imitation motor vehicle parts broken up.
However, the imitator continued to secure the Chinese rights to the Freudenberg brand.
We failed to do this ourselves, since family names cannot be protected in Germany, says Hanno Wentzler, CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialties in Munich.
The trademark office CTMO rejected the Munich-based company&#39;s objection.
Freudenberg was right in the next two instances, but the opposing party is still fighting to this day.
You have to be really careful
The matter is now before the Supreme Court.
Wentzler is confident of bringing the matter to a good conclusion and praises the professionalism of the courts.
But he also says: &quot;The process is extremely complex and costs us a lot of time, money and nerves.&quot;
The internal costs could hardly be quantified, the company archives even had to look through hundred-year-old files to provide evidence.
Five years ago, Freudenberg unsuccessfully offered the other side a &quot;high six-digit euro amount&quot; for settlement.
&quot;That shows how much it&#39;s worth to us,&quot; says Wentzler.
The dangers in the Far East even threaten to spill back to Europe.
Namely, when imitators secure unprotected brands there.
A Chinese manufacturer wanted to register the name Freudenberg for shoes and leather in Germany.
The group has long since given up this business area, but it was still able to avert the registration.
&quot;You have to be extremely careful,&quot; says Wentzler.
Both he and the lawyer Pattloch advise German companies to be very careful when doing business with China.
It&#39;s not enough to rely on international trademark rights; rather, foreigners should &quot;register everything that is somehow worth protecting in China,&quot; as Wentzler says.
Otherwise it can be much more expensive than the registration.
In fact: If Freudenberg loses in the last act of his brand drama, then you would probably have to pay the other party license fees for your own name, explains Wentzler.
Or we will be pushed out of the market in the segment in question.
