The most difficult profession in the world: the human workhorses of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the porters of the Indonesian volcano put their lives and health at risk when they carry 70 kilos of sulfur over the steep, stony paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell and others literally work in hell.
Such is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who make a living extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano on the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, he must descend every day to the bottom of his crater, where the sulphurous gas escaping from the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After breaking out large sulfur stones, which can weigh up to 70 kilograms in total, he carries them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders down the sloping stone paths.
It&#39;s only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to a height of 2,386 meters, but it takes the exhausted porters more than 40 minutes to climb at a turtle pace, balancing and stepping carefully. so they don&#39;t slip and fall.
They know that every step can cost her life, as happened to a French tourist who fell on the cliffs of Kawah Ijen years ago.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 cents for every kilo of sulfur they mine.
Once at the top, they make their way between the tourists, who take pictures of them like circus monkeys, and walk three kilometers with the tiringly heavy baskets to the scales, which a mining company has set up a little further down at an altitude of 1850 meters
The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, which since 1960 has exploited the deposits in the volcano and (never put it better) its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euro cents) for every kilo of sulfur.
She then sells these to the petrochemical industry for 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) each, because this mineral is widespread in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
&quot;Since we usually carry 70 kg, we get about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each trip,&quot; explains Anto, who normally does three trips a day.
It takes him three hours each way, after which he&#39;s exhausted, but at the end of the day he&#39;s saved 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros).
What looks like a miserable wage for such inhumane effort is three times what he would earn working in the fields.
&quot;The daily wages of the miners here, where the coffee harvest is 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) a day and the average monthly income is 2 million rupees (167 euros), is very high,&quot; explains the porter, who previously worked as a bricklayer the tourist island of Bali.
There he was earning 75,000 rupees a day and the work wasn&#39;t that hard, but Anto has returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village nearby, for a reason that is so important in Indonesia as the sulfur is: &quot;I married a girl from Bali where they are Hindus and I took her to Java to convert her to Islam&quot;.
Anto has asthma, is breathing with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated from the toxic gases.
For three years now, 27-year-old Anto has been risking his life at Kawah Ijen, whose sulfur has already left its mark on him, even though he covers his face with a mask and special glasses.
Anto has asthma, is breathing with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated from the toxic gases from the volcano.
This is the price he has to pay for achieving his dream.
&quot;I&#39;ll work here for another two years because I want to open a shop or learn Spanish or French,&quot; he promises in more than acceptable English.
This likeable and intelligent, but life-strung young man could work as a tourist guide, waiter or receptionist at a hotel, but instead he does the work of a donkey.
Sharing a filthy wooden hut with other porters, he gets up at 2 a.m. every morning because the sulfur emanates even at night, where its distinctive yellow color glistens bluish in the dark.
Defying the shadows, he descends into the crater by the light of a small headlamp on his helmet that he bought with his own money.
Around 400 porters load baskets of sulfur onto their shoulders at the bottom of the crater.
Despite its large profits, the mining company has not mechanized sulfur mining to save costs and does not supply any equipment to the porters, who work on their own account and are paid by the weight.
They also do not get a share of the 30,000 rupees ($2.5) surcharge per camera that the wardens of this nature park, along with the 15,000 rupees ($1.2) entrance fee, charge tourists to take photos of the volcano and of human donkeys come.
&quot;This work is for the animals, not for humans,&quot; protests Madrusin, a burly, 42-year-old porter who has been working at Kawah Ijen for three decades since leaving school.
Able to carry up to 110kg, he says he will continue &quot;as long as he can&quot; because he needs the money to raise his three children, aged between 10 and 18.
I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life.
Even if the sulfur burns your throat and your eyes itch, if the wind suddenly turns and the miners are trapped in the thick columns rising from the crater, the men are so tough that nobody complains of serious illnesses ... except for them, of course the usual breathing problems, osteoarthritis, knee pain and blisters on the shoulders that have been deformed by the weight of the baskets.
With the basket on his back, Unainik, aged 53, is only able to carry 50 kg.
Every day he and his companions quarry 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which are transported by three trucks along a goat path between the bushes to the camp in Tamansari, 18 kilometers away.
&quot;I&#39;m not going to retire, I&#39;m going to die here because the volcano has been my whole life,&quot; explains Unainik, opening his mouth wide and missing a few teeth.
Of his five children, the eldest, at 30, also works as a sulfur porter.
Time goes by, but the misery continues for generation after generation in one of the toughest professions in the world: that of those who work as human pack donkeys at Kawah Ijen.
